<HL>
   Dutch Retail Sales Increase
</HL>
<DATE>
12/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   AMSTERDAM -- Led by strong growth in the non-food sector,
Dutch retail sales in October climbed 9.6% from a year
earlier, the Dutch Central Bureau of Statistics said.
   Though non-food retail sales rose 12% in October, sales at
department stores were up just 2%, continuing to lag behind
those of other retailers, as they have all year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the non-food sector, these sales increases were posted:
clothing, 12%; white goods, 9.5%; hardware articles, 9.1%;
household articles, 22%; books and magazines, 20%;
photographic articles, 20%; and optical goods, 13%. With an
average price increase of 16% for motor fuels, sales at
gasoline stations increased 18%. In the food sector, butcher
sales rose 11% and bakery sales 8.6%.
</TEXT>
