<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Museum Musings: Never a Blockbuster at the Hotel Salm
   ----
   By Nicholas King
</HL>
<DATE>
12/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<LP>
   Paris -- Stepping out on the terrace of the Musee d'Orsay,
high above the Seine and the chestnut ramble of the Tuileries
Gardens and beneath a raft of white and silver clouds, you
see the landscape of the impressionists whose canvases are
fixed directly behind in the galleries you have just left.
   A Frenchman I know protests he is "scandalized" by the way
the Monets and the Pisarros and the Sisleys are hung there,
crowded together on dull gray walls in ill-lit rooms,
lacking, in short, the eclat they had when they could be seen
in the Jeu de Paume.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It is hard to know what is right any more about such
paintings after having been imprisoned so long by their
fashion, a fashion that has focused a preponderant attention
on the art of late-19th-century France. We have been kept
staring at the same few painters for 50 years now as their
prices have soared into the tens of millions of dollars.
   Still, that is not the fault of the Musee d'Orsay. In
fact, once up off the ground, the visitor becomes happily
lost in the iron beams and the industrial glass of the
suburban railroad station the place once was. The great
luminous clocks that face the Seine are still the glory of
the art nouveau facade: Now you can squint out at Paris from
behind the huge hands and heroic Roman numerals.
   Across the rue de Bellechasse stands a quite different
museum, that of the Legion d'Honneur, tucked away behind the
serene neoclassic facades of the Hotel Salm, a good place to
go after the hubbub of the Musee d'Orsay. The exhibits
consist, very restfully, of ribbons and medals and
memorabilia of Napoleon I, who founded the order. There are
other displays of earlier orders of the old monarchy, notably
the order of the Holy Ghost, the one with the blue sash or
cordon bleu, familiar to all those who know the portraits of
the Bourbon kings. A connoisseur's item is a full-length
tapestry representation of the Emperor Napoleon III stepping
forward from what looks like a great ermine bathrobe.
   The Hotel Salm, which ironically was finished in 1789 and
survived the revolution only to be burned by the Commune, was
restored by the Legion of Honor and taken for its
headquarters. Its shallow dome adorned with statues looks,
leaffringed, across the Seine. Its handsomely proportioned
windows, sweeping to the gleaming parquet of the floor, are
themselves swept with thickly lined curtains of yellow silk.
   Could we visit the rest of the building, now that our tour
of the museum's few rooms is finished? "Only 25 visitors a
month," snaps the secretary from behind her formidable lobby
desk, her blue-gray eyes snapping in time. "We are already
subscribed fully for this month. If you wish to put your name
down, it will be for the next visit six weeks hence."
   "Remember, only 25 visitors at a time. Monsieur le
Chancelier is most inflexible on this point and there shall
be no exceptions," she continued. Perhaps it's a good idea.
The prehistoric cave at Lascaux had to close after only 30
years because of the pollution caused by an excessive number
of human visitors.
   Up at the corner of the rue de Bellechasse and the
Boulevard St. Germain, there is an elegant butcher shop next
to the bus stop. I watched the young butcher bone a leg of
lamb, neat as a surgeon, twirling it around with string,
finishing smartly with a single, snapped-off knot, and then
setting down on the wide wooden block before him a
rose-mahogany bundle of admirable meat geometrically laced
with white.
   An elderly couple was studying this ritual with fierce
attention. It was their meat he was preparing of course,
leaning over the glass counter as the lamb was juggled to the
scale to be weighed, tossed on a paper and wrapped
cracklingly for the cashier, an aloof, white-haired woman,
seated high at her counter.
   The butcher at once released himself into another sequence
of graceful clockwork, fencing and flicking his knife around
a large lump of white fat, which he soon transformed into a
succulent veal kidney, again tied and trimmed -- just so] And
here was the No. 68 bus.
   ---
   Mr. King is the director of the Foreign Press Center in
New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901220-0163
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901220-0163.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Banks Fail to React to Fed Rate Moves;
   Mortgage Rates Drop, but Sales Still Sag
   ---
   Prospective Buyers Show
   Interest, but Are Wary
   Of Economic Slowdown
   ----
   By Jim Carlton
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   A sustained drop in fixed-mortgage rates to the lowest
level in nearly four years has failed so far to boost sagging
home sales.
   According to a survey of 2,000 lenders by HSH Associates
of Butler, N.J., the average 30-year rate as of last Friday
had fallen to 9.66%, the lowest since April 1987, when it was
9.5%. But real-estate agents and builders around the country
are reporting little or no new movement in the residential
market. And they expect little change until the underlying
causes of consumer concern -- high home prices in some areas,
battered regional economies, fears of a serious national
recession and the Persian Gulf crisis -- are resolved one way
or another.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Everybody is scared to death to make a move in any
direction," said Alfred Gobar, a real-estate consultant in
Brea, Calif.
   Of course, housing isn't dead in all parts of the country.
Homes are still relatively easy to sell in certain areas,
particularly in the Northwest and Midwest. Moreover, analysts
agree that lower interest rates have to be regarded as a
longer-term positive for the market. But right now, they
aren't sufficient to overcome the uncertainties that have
walloped housing sales on both coasts and sent housing starts
plunging. Indeed, a government survey indicates that the
average fixed-rate mortgage available this year will be the
lowest in 12 years, but home sales nonetheless shrank
significantly.
   The Commerce Department reported yesterday that overall
starts were up 9% for November, but the increase was
concentrated in apartment construction while single-family
starts dropped to their lowest level in eight years. If
current trends persist, some economists predict overall
starts for 1991 will fall to a post-war low well under one
million units.
   Even though the lowered interest rates have failed to
jump-start the housing market, prospective buyers are showing
more interest. Jim Arnold, vice president of sales for The
Mortgage Market, a northern California lender offering a
9.25% fixed rate with 2.5 points, said more people are
calling in for information about the rates but have yet to
act.
   "It starts with the phone calls and people asking a lot of
questions," Mr. Arnold said. "Then, usually, they come in two
weeks later and ask for a loan."
   Randall W. Lewis, executive vice president of Lewis Homes,
a builder in California and Nevada, said the interest rates
have drawn more people to the company's sales lots -- though
not to buy.
   "They come in saying, `We're just checking. We want to
make sure the time is right,'" Mr. Lewis said.
   A few agents and builders report improved sales because of
sharply falling prices. In Boston, Douglas Bray, president of
Century 21 Cityside, said his sales are up 25% from last year
due to lower prices and reduced inventory. He added that the
lowered interest rates have been instrumental in not impeding
sales.
   Lower interest rates aren't nearly as important as they
were eight years ago when the fixed rate dropped down from a
peak in the upper-teens, invigorating home sales, said J.
Larry Sorsby, vice president of finance for Hovnanian
Enterprises, a Red Bank, N.J., builder of less-expensive
homes. Today's rate, while favorable, is still only a
drop-off from the 10- to 11-point range, which was also
favorable, Mr. Sorsby said.
   "Certainly, lower interest rates will help," Mr. Sorsby
said. "But the Northeast has been hit pretty hard with the
layoffs on Wall Street, combined with lower job growth and
the Mideast crisis."
   More than anything else, the lower interest rates provide
a necessary foundation for the market's eventual recovery.
Lower home prices are the other ingredient for recovery,
along with a restoration of consumer confidence. Some
industry officials feel the lowered rates, in and of
themselves, can help bring buyers' confidence back on track.
   "It will help restore some confidence in the housing
market with the prospect that interest rates are pretty good
and things are okay," said Harley E. Rouda, a Columbus, Ohio,
realtor and president of the National Association of
Realtors.
   (See related story: "Prime Is Kept Unchanged In Bid to
Offset Losses; January Drop Expected" -- WSJ Dec. 20, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
